INTRODUCTION TO MACHINE LEARNING ASSIGNMENT¶

ROBERTO BERROCAL¶

BUSINESS CONTEXT¶

This dataset can be used to predict the chronic kidney disease, and it can be collected from the hospital nearly 2 months of period.

Data dictionary:

The aim of the dataset is to predict Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) accurately based on some features.

The dataset is from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/336/chronic+kidney+disease and each row represent a patient’s data. This business problem is important because contributes to the health sector on how be more precisely while trying to detect (CKD). The data has been collected for around 2 months. The formulation of this problem to a machine learning task would be a supervised learning classification task. The goal is to predict if a patient has CKD or not, so the target is the “Class” variable and is a dichotomic one, where (1 = CKD and 0= No CKD). At first sight, the data has some quality issues like null values within some features. Also, there are some categorical features that need to be processed for the modeling part.

There are some columms that have not curated values, like "\tno" and "\tyes". We need to clean these columns:

  • DiabetesMellitus
  • CoronaryArteryDisease
  • Class

After cleaning those values in that 3 columns, I will convert "Class" to a 1 and 0 values.

In [186]:
df['DiabetesMellitus'].replace(to_replace = {'\tno':'no','\tyes':'yes',' yes':'yes'},inplace=True)

df['CoronaryArteryDisease'].replace(to_replace = '\tno', value='no', inplace= True)

df['Class'].replace(to_replace = {'ckd\t': 'ckd', 'notckd': 'not ckd'}, inplace=True)
In [187]:
# Here I change the categorical values to numerical values (1 for positive and 0 for negative)
df['Class'] = df['Class'].map({'ckd': 0, 'not ckd': 1})

df['Class'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Class'], errors='coerce')

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 25))

for i, col in enumerate(numerical_cols):
    plt.subplot(num_rows, num_cols, i + 1)
    sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of: {col}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

INSIGHTS:

Age: The feature has a distribution very near to normal with a slight skew to the right. It seems that more patients are between 40 and 70 years. There are not critical outliers.

Blood Pressure: We can see some peaks around 70, 80 and 90. This could be due to the nature of the sampling. Also, there are some higher values above 125 that can be treated as outliers or clinical cases.

Specific Gravity: This feature has a bimodal distribution. It can suggest the existence of two subgroups within the data.

Albumin and Sugar: Both are strongly skewed to the left, with a high number of zeros. This says that many patients do not have high levels of albumin or sugar.

Blood glucose random: This variable has right skewed distribution with some high values. I would be better if we could know that these values are not data

Blood Urea and Serum Creatinine: Both variables are strongly right skewed. These indicators can vary in patients with kidney disease. Some high values can be considered as outliers.

Sodium and Potassium: Both of these variables seem more concentrated with tighter distributions. Sodium shows values around 130-150. Potassium has a right skewed behavior and a narrower distribution

Hemoglobin and Packed Cell Volume: Both of them seem to have a normal distribution with slight skewness to the left. These are common indicators in blood tests for patients with CKD

With Blood Cell Count and Red Blood Cell Count: These features have a very close to normal distribution behavior but have some high values on the right.

Coronary Artery Disease: Few patients have coronary artery disease.

Appetite: Most patients report good appetite, although there is a small group with bad appetite with is a sign of disease presence.

Peda Edema and Anemia: The majority of the patients suffer from both edema and anemia. Both are common symptoms of CKD.

Hemoglobin Packed Cell Volume and Red Blood Cell Count: Class 1 have lower levels of this blood indicators. This support the presence of anemia in CKD patients

# Here I define three functions to impute the missing values with the median, mean and mode
def impute_median(feature):
    median = df[feature].median()
    df[feature] = df[feature].fillna(median)

def impute_mean(feature):
    mean = df[feature].mean()
    df[feature] = df[feature].fillna(mean)

def impute_mode(feature):
    mode = df[feature].mode()[0]
    df[feature] = df[feature].fillna(mode)
In [199]:

    impute_mean(col)

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV


param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 130, 150],
    'max_depth': [10, 11, 12],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 3, 5],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
}

# set the classifier
ran_for_class = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=0)

# set up the grid search with 5-fold cross validation
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=ran_for_class, 
                           param_grid=param_grid, 
                           cv=5, 
                           scoring='accuracy', 
                           n_jobs=-1,  # Use all processors
                           verbose=1)

# fit the grid search
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

FINAL DISCUSSION¶

I have used the following models to this dataset:

  • Logistic Regression
  • K-Nearest Neighbors
  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • Support Vector Machine

The best model was Random Forest because of its accuracy, showed in the table above (0.966667), so it was the model selected for the hyper parameter tunning step.

During the grid search, it optimized some hyperparameters like:

  • n_estimators
  • max_depth
  • min_samples_leaf
  • min_samples_split
  • criterion

After the hyperparameter tunning, the best random forest model got a validation accuracy of 0.9786.

After evaluating the best model to the test dataset, it obtained 1 of accuracy. The conclusion is that the model generalizes very well to the test data, due to the hyperparameter tunning.

Some strengths of the solution are that almost every model gets a excellent accuracy score, except for the KNN model, concluding that the dataset is good for predictive approaches. Also, the best model (Random Forest) is very robust to overfitting due to its ensemble technique and the validation and accuracy scores suggest that the model is not overfitting.

One of the limitations is that Random Forest models are complex to interpret, especially the parameter selection compared to other models like Logistic Regression. The model is known for being a black box. Data quality is also a limitation because the model’s success relies on both the quality and quantity of the data, that means that unrepresentative features can affect directly to the model performance. Although the model performed perfectly on the test dataset, this could imply a slight overfitting, the suggestion is to gather more rows to test again the model and its performance.

The proposed machine learning pipeline using Random Forest could help with the automation of the prediction of CKD in real time, improving operational efficiency and reducing manual work. Due to its health approach, the predictions can be used to prioritize treatments or critical patients, saying this the model is ready to be deployed.

The most informative features are:

  • Specific Gravity
  • Hemoglobin
  • Packed Cell Volume
  • Serum Creatinine
  • Red Blood Cell Count

These features have a biological meaning related to the kidney and with health. The high importance of this feature indicates that they are key to the prediction of the chronic kidney disease.

Recommendations:

Increase the size of the dataset, 400 rows seem to be a short size dataset trying to gather more data to test the model should be included.

To improve the interpretability of the model, more advanced techniques like SHAP (Shapley Additive explanations) or LIME (Local interpretable Model agnostic Explanations) can be applied to explain better the features and its importance, making the model more interpretable for stakeholders.
